{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fd889729-920a-4e90-8bae-a5bfab89d7b8","content":"Here's how to connect your C# MCP server to the **MCP Inspector**:\n\n### 1. Run the Inspector\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\n\nThis opens a web UI (usually at `http://localhost:6274`).\n\n### 2. Configure the connection\n\nIn the Inspector UI:\n\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourMcpServer.csproj`\n\nOr if you have a built DLL:\n\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `/path/to/YourMcpServer.dll`\n\nThen click **Connect**.\n\n### 3. Debug\n\nOnce connected, you can:\n\n- Browse **Tools**, **Resources**, and **Prompts** your server exposes.\n- **Invoke tools** with custom inputs and see the JSON responses.\n- View the raw **JSON-RPC messages** in the message log for troubleshooting.\n\n### Tips\n\n- **Environment variables** can be set in the Inspector UI if your server needs them (e.g., connection strings).\n- If your server writes logs to **stderr**, they'll appear in the Inspector's log pane (stdout is reserved for MCP protocol messages).\n- To attach a **debugger**, add a launch delay or `Debugger.Launch()` call in your server startup, then attach from your IDE before connecting.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c7c2a8da-40ba-454a-855d-e5345d8da659","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to connect a C# MCP server (using stdio transport) to the MCP Inspector for interactive debugging. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to explore a codebase. I can answer directly.","outputTokens":399},"id":"7db7ba5d-e20c-4096-bd0d-ef1de27da444","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:50:52.912Z","parentId":"a34f4a3c-fd5f-4eca-ac1b-8ddc8c480021"}
